3.text:
The most direct way to use Tevm is with the raw createTevmNode API:
import { createTevmNode } from &#x27;tevm&#x27;
// tevm/actions has many useful high level actions to interact with
// the tevm api including the entire json rpc api
import {
  callHandler,
  setAccountHandler,
  getAccountHandler,
} from &#x27;tevm/actions&#x27;

const node = createTevmNode()

// Execute a contract call
const result = await callHandler(node)({
  to: &#x27;0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890&#x27;,
  data: &#x27;0x...&#x27;,
  value: 0n
})

// Set account state
await tevmSetAccountHandler(node)({
  address: &#x27;0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890&#x27;,
  balance: 1000000000000000000n // 1 ETH
})

// Get account state
const account = await getAccountHandler(node)({
  address: &#x27;0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890&#x27;
})

4.text:
For a more familiar developer experience, you can use Tevm with Viem:
You can still use the Raw Tevm Node API referencing client.transport.tevm
import { createMemoryClient, http } from &#x27;tevm&#x27;
import { optimism } from &#x27;tevm/common&#x27;

// Create a client that forks from Optimism mainnet
const client = createMemoryClient({
  fork: {
    transport: http(&#x27;https://mainnet.optimism.io&#x27;)({}),
    blockTag: &#x27;latest&#x27;,
  },
  common: optimism,
})

// Use viem&#x27;s public, wallet, or test actions
const block = await client.getBlock({ blockTag: &#x27;latest&#x27; })
console.log(block)

// Mix with Tevm actions
const testAddress = &#x27;0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890&#x27;
await client.tevmSetAccount({
  address: testAddress,
  balance: 1000000000000000000n // 1 ETH
})

// Get account state
const account = await client.tevmGetAccount({ address: testAddress })
console.log(account)

// Use the raw Tevm node api via `client.transport.tevm`
const vm = await client.transport.tevm.getVm()
const block = await vm.blockchain.getBlockByTag(&#x27;latest&#x27;)

